  "doc_id": "61503",
  "text": "Global energy minimization methods These approaches formulate depth upscaling as an optimization problem which employs data fidelity and regularization term [CITATION_1] . Diebel et al. [CITATION_2] develop Markov Random Field (MRF)-based energy minimization framework, which fuses the LR depth map and the corresponding HR intensity image, but it tends to generate oversmooth results and is also sensitive to noises. In order to maintain local structures, Park et al. [CITATION_3] use a nonlocal means filter (MRF+NLM) to regularize the depth map, but jaggy artifacts occur in some boundaries. A more recent approach of Ferstl et al. [CITATION_4] utilizes an anisotropic diffusion tensor to guide the depth map upsampling (TGV), and the tensor is calculated from a HR intensity image; however, it is not smooth in some internal areas. Aodha et al. [CITATION_5] treat depth image upsampling as MRF labeling problem which matches LR depth image patches to HR patches from an ancillary database; the training of data, matching, and fusion are quite computationally intensive. In [CITATION_6] , an adaptive intensity-guided regression method is proposed for depth upsampling, but its relative high computational complexity would limit its practical applications.",
